or as a protection against corruption and conflict of interest and as a spur to raising standards. It provides the first full-length treatment of the evolving integrity agenda in the United Kingdom. The book traces the impact of the Committee on Standards in Public Life which set out the Nolan principles in its first report in 1995 and examines how those principles have been applied in different sectors – Parliament, the executive, the civil service, local government and the devolved governments – and how they have been applied to the problems of party funding and lobbying. Finally, it assesses the changing level of support for the Committee’s mission and the impact of its work both on the quality of public life itself and on public confidence.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAbuse of administrative powerxPreventionxGreat Britain. 0aAbuse of administrative powerzGreat BritainxPrevention. 0aPublic administrationxMoral and ethical aspectsxGreat BritainxGreat Britain. 0aPublic administrationxMoral and ethical aspectszGreat Britain. 4aPolitical Studies 2019. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh  aCommittee on Standards in public life.  aConflict of interest.  aCorruption.  aEthical risk.  aIntegrity issues.  aRegulation.1 aHine, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeele, Gillian, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aPeele, Gillian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2016 eBook-Packagez978311128282440uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978178499708340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781784997083423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781784997083/original  a978-3-11-128282-4  Manchester Unive